(88, NULL, 15, 1, '<p>Which of the following is the correct expression for differentiating \\(f(x)=x^2-4 x\\) from first principles?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1 mark]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 5, 7, '<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br />\r\nRecalling the first principles formula: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{gathered} f(x)=x^2-4 x \\\\ f(x+h)=(x+h)^2-4(x+h) \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, substituting this into first principles: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{(x+h)^2-4(x+h)-\\left(x^2-4 x\\right)}{h} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>$$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{(x-h)^2-4(x+h)+\\left(x^2-4 x\\right)}{h} $$</p>', '60', 'Easy', '1', 1, NULL, '2024-03-24 11:40:17', '2024-03-19 16:33:53'),
