(181, NULL, 36, 1, '<p>$$ \\text { What is the derivative of } f(x)=\\frac{\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^3} \\text { ? } $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>', 'Both', 5, 5, 9, '<p>Solution:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the quotient rule \\(\\left(\\frac{u}{v}\\right)^{\\prime}=\\frac{u^{\\prime} v-v^{\\prime} u}{v^2}\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{\\left(\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2\\right)^{\\prime}(2 x-1)^3-\\left((2 x-1)^3\\right)^{\\prime}\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} $$ Remember that for chain rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\left(\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2\\right)^{\\prime}=2(2 x-1)\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^1 \\\\ &amp; \\left((2 x-1)^3\\right)^{\\prime}=2 \\cdot 3(2 x-1)^2=6(2 x-1)^2 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{2(2 x-1)\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)(2 x-1)^3-6(2 x-1)^2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} \\\\ f^{\\prime}(x) &amp; =\\frac{2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)(2 x-1)^4-6(2 x-1)^2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} \\end{aligned} $$ No need to simplify or factorise any further since this is one of our answer options! Note that this question is tricky because it tests both chain rule and quotient rule!</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>$$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\frac{\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)(2 x-1)^4-3(2 x-1)^2\\left(x^2-x+1\\right)^2}{(2 x-1)^6} $$</p>', '180', 'Hard', '2', 1, NULL, '2024-03-24 11:37:31', '2024-03-19 19:27:32'),
