(232, NULL, 48, 1, '<p>A water tank is holding \\(9025 L\\)&nbsp;of water. The water is slowly drained out of the tank, such that the following equation predicts that the volume, \\(V\\)&nbsp;litres, or water that will remain in the tank after \\(t\\)&nbsp;minutes is given by: $$ V=9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. How long until the tank is empty?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\nii. What volume of water is predicted to remain after half an hour?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\niii. At what rate does the model predict that the water will be draining from the tank after 40 minutes?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\niv. At what time will the water drain from the tank the fastest?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p>', 'Both', 5, 5, 12, '<p>i. The tank is empty when \\(V=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} 0= &amp; 9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; \\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)=0 \\\\ &amp; 1=\\frac{t}{95} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=95 \\end{aligned} $$ It therefore takes 95 minutes for the tank to be empty<br />\r\n<br />\r\nii. When \\(t=30\\), finding the value of \\(V\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} V &amp; =9025\\left(1-\\frac{30}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; =9025\\left(\\frac{65}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; =4225 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, there will be \\(4225 \\mathrm{~L}\\) of water left in the tank after 30 minutes<br />\r\n<br />\r\niii. Considering the first derivative of \\(V\\) in rate of change: $$ \\begin{aligned} V &amp; =9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ V^{\\prime} &amp; =9025 \\times 2 \\times-\\frac{1}{95}\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right) \\text { [Chain Rule] } \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; =-190\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =-190+2 t \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, to find the rate it is draining when \\(t=40\\), sub into \\(V^{\\prime}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} V^{\\prime} &amp; =-190+2(40) \\\\ &amp; =-110 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the rate of drainage should be \\(110 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\) when \\(t=40\\). Note that we do not include the negative sign since drainage already represents a decrease in volume.<br />\r\n<br />\r\niv. The question is asking us when the water drains from the tank the fastest. In other words, we are finding when \\(V^{\\prime}\\) has the most negative value [Since draining is a rate of decrease, it is negative and we want our value to be as negative as possible] $$ V^{\\prime}=-190+2 t $$ Since \\(V^{\\prime}\\) is a straight line, it is most negative when \\(t=0\\), where: $$ V^{\\prime}=-190+0=-190 $$ Hence, drainage is fastest when \\(t=0\\)<br />\r\n<strong>Tricky question!</strong></p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\\(95\\) minutes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\\(4225\\) L</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part iii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\\(110\\) litres per minute</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part iv:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$t=95$$</p>', '540', 'Hard', '5', 1, NULL, '2024-03-20 09:12:28', '2024-03-20 09:12:28'),
(233, NULL, 48, 2, '<p>A water tank is holding \\(9025 L\\)&nbsp;of water. The water is slowly drained out of the tank, such that the following equation predicts that the volume, \\(V\\)&nbsp;litres, or water that will remain in the tank after \\(t\\)&nbsp;minutes is given by: $$ V=9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. How long until the tank is empty?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\nii. What volume of water is predicted to remain after half an hour?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\niii. At what rate does the model predict that the water will be draining from the tank after 40 minutes?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[2 marks]}\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\niv. At what time will the water drain from the tank the fastest?<br />\r\n\\(\\text{[1 mark]}\\)</p>', 'Both', 5, 5, 12, '<p>i. The tank is empty when \\(V=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} 0= &amp; 9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; \\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)=0 \\\\ &amp; 1=\\frac{t}{95} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=95 \\end{aligned} $$ It therefore takes 95 minutes for the tank to be empty<br />\r\n<br />\r\nii. When \\(t=30\\), finding the value of \\(V\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} V &amp; =9025\\left(1-\\frac{30}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; =9025\\left(\\frac{65}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ &amp; =4225 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, there will be \\(4225 \\mathrm{~L}\\) of water left in the tank after 30 minutes<br />\r\n<br />\r\niii. Considering the first derivative of \\(V\\) in rate of change: $$ \\begin{aligned} V &amp; =9025\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right)^2 \\\\ V^{\\prime} &amp; =9025 \\times 2 \\times-\\frac{1}{95}\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right) \\text { [Chain Rule] } \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; =-190\\left(1-\\frac{t}{95}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =-190+2 t \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, to find the rate it is draining when \\(t=40\\), sub into \\(V^{\\prime}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} V^{\\prime} &amp; =-190+2(40) \\\\ &amp; =-110 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, the rate of drainage should be \\(110 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\) when \\(t=40\\). Note that we do not include the negative sign since drainage already represents a decrease in volume.<br />\r\n<br />\r\niv. The question is asking us when the water drains from the tank the fastest. In other words, we are finding when \\(V^{\\prime}\\) has the most negative value [Since draining is a rate of decrease, it is negative and we want our value to be as negative as possible] $$ V^{\\prime}=-190+2 t $$ Since \\(V^{\\prime}\\) is a straight line, it is most negative when \\(t=0\\), where: $$ V^{\\prime}=-190+0=-190 $$ Hence, drainage is fastest when \\(t=0\\)<br />\r\n<strong>Tricky question!</strong></p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\\(95\\) minutes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\\(4225\\) L</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part iii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\\(-110\\) litres per minute</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part iv:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$t=95$$</p>', '540', 'Hard', '5', 1, NULL, '2024-03-20 09:12:28', '2024-03-20 09:12:28'),
