(452, NULL, 90, 1, '<p>The function \\(f(x)\\)&nbsp;is a continuous odd function. Which of the following statements is necessarily true?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\ni.&nbsp; &nbsp;\\(f(x^2)\\) is even&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nii.&nbsp; \\(f(x)+f(-x)=0\\)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\niii. \\(f(0)=0\\)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1 mark]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 7, 28, '<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br />\r\nSince we know that \\(f(x)\\) is odd, therefore: $$ f(-x)=-f(x) $$ Looking at statement i: For the function \\(f\\left(x^2\\right)\\) : $$ f\\left((-x)^2\\right)=f\\left(x^2\\right) $$ Hence, since \\(f\\left((-x)^2\\right)=f\\left(x^2\\right)\\), it can be said that \\(f\\left(x^2\\right)\\) is even and statement \\(\\mathrm{i}\\) is true Looking at statement ii: $$ f(x)+f(-x)=0 $$ Since \\(f(-x)=-f(x)\\) : $$ \\therefore f(x)-f(x)=0 $$ Hence, statement ii is true<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLooking at statement iii:&nbsp;<br />\r\nSince it is known that \\(f(-x)=-f(x)\\), then \\(f(0)\\) MUST equal to 0&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnother way to imagine this is that since \\(f(x)\\) is odd, it has point symmetry, meaning that it must intersect the origin, so \\(f(0)=0\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHence, statement iii is true Therefore, all three statements are true!</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>i only</p>', '120', 'Hard', '1', 1, NULL, '2024-03-24 13:51:11', '2024-03-24 18:48:14'),
