(478, NULL, 96, 1, '<p>Let \\(f(x)=2-x\\) and \\(g(x)=6+x\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\nWhat is the domain of the function: $$ h(x)=\\ln \\left\\{\\frac{f(-x)}{g(-x)}\\right\\} ? $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 7, 29, '<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br />\r\nFirst, simplifying our logarithm using log laws: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\ln \\left\\{\\frac{f(-x)}{g(-x)}\\right\\}=\\ln ( &amp; f(-x))-\\ln (g(-x)) \\\\ f(-x) &amp; =2-(-x) \\\\ &amp; =2+x \\\\ g(-x) &amp; =6+(-x) \\\\ &amp; =6-x \\\\ \\therefore \\ln (f(-x))-\\ln (g(-x)) &amp; =\\ln (2+x)-\\ln (6-x) \\end{aligned} $$ The expression inside a logarithm cannot be negative or equal to 0 . Hence: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 2+x&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; x&gt;-2 \\\\ &amp; 6-x&gt;0 \\\\ &amp; x&lt;6 \\end{aligned} $$ Now combining these two domains simultaneously:<br />\r\n$$ \\therefore-2&lt;x&lt;6$$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(x&lt;-2\\)</p>', '180', 'Medium', '2', 1, NULL, '2024-03-24 19:01:39', '2024-03-24 19:01:39'),
