(550, NULL, 110, 1, '<p>In the diagram below, use the sine rule to find the value of \\(\\theta\\), correct to the nearest minute</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/a7c526260317ee61d3092a42d4c1b82d.png\" style=\"height:378px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 128, '<p>Recalling the sine rule for finding angles:<br />\r\n$$<br />\r\n\\frac{\\sin \\theta}{17}=\\frac{\\sin 33^{\\circ}}{11}<br />\r\n$$$$<br />\r\n\\begin{aligned}<br />\r\n\\therefore \\sin \\theta &amp; =17 \\times \\frac{\\sin 33^{\\circ}}{11} \\\\<br />\r\n&amp; =0.841715<br />\r\n\\end{aligned}<br />\r\n$$$$<br />\r\n\\therefore \\theta=57^{\\circ} 19^{\\prime} \\text { (nearest minute) }<br />\r\n$$However, we must check for ambiguous case in sine rule:<br />\r\n$$<br />\r\n\\begin{aligned}<br />\r\n\\theta &amp; =180^{\\circ}-57^{\\circ} 19^{\\prime} \\\\<br />\r\n&amp; =122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}<br />\r\n\\end{aligned}<br />\r\n$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since \\(122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}&lt;180^{\\circ}\\), then this means that \\(\\theta=122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}\\) may also be a solution!<br />\r\n$$<br />\r\n\\therefore \\theta=57^{\\circ} 19^{\\prime} \\text { OR } 122^{\\circ} 41^{\\prime}<br />\r\n$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that forgetting to check for ambiguous case here would lose one mark.|</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(\\theta=57^{\\circ}19^{\\prime}\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-25 15:12:03', '2024-03-25 15:12:03'),
