\triangle D A B=\\frac{1}{2} a b \\sin \\theta \\\\ &amp;=\\frac{1}{2} \\times(A B) \\times(A D) \\times \\sin \\angle D A B \\\\ &amp;=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 4 \\times 4 \\times \\sin \\frac{2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp;=8 \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\\\ &amp;=4 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m}^2 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\text { Total Area }=20 \\pi+4 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~m}^2 \\end{aligned} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$DB=3\\sqrt{3} \\text{ m}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$\\text{Total Area }=30\\pi+3\\sqrt{3} \\text{ m}^2$$</p>', '420', 'Medium', '4', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:15:47', '2024-03-26 18:15:47'),
(609, NULL, 122, 1, '<p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" style=\"height:301px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(x=3\\sqrt{3}\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:18:23', '2024-03-26 18:18:23'),
(610, NULL, 122, 2, '<p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" style=\"height:301px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>', 'correct', '<p>\\(x=3\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:18:23', '2024-03-26 18:18:23'),
(611, NULL, 122, 3, '<p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" style=\"height:301px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(x=\\frac{3\\sqrt3}{2}\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:18:23', '2024-03-26 18:18:23'),
(612, NULL, 122, 4, '<p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" style=\"height:301px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(x=\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{3}}\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:18:23', '2024-03-26 18:18:23');
