(613, NULL, 122, 5, '<p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" style=\"height:301px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(x=\\sqrt{3}\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:18:23', '2024-03-26 18:18:23'),
(614, NULL, 122, 6, '<p>In the diagram below, \\(\\triangle A B C\\) is right angled at \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), with \\(\\angle B A C=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\) and \\(A B=6 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). RP is a circular arc with centre at \\(A\\) and RQ is a circular arc with centre at \\(B\\). If \\(A R\\) has length \\(x \\mathrm{~cm}\\), find the value of \\(x\\) for which the areas of the sectors ARP and BRQ are equal</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f6be37042842db26c29962df502692d7.png\" style=\"height:301px; width:500px\" /></p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>Since \\(A R=x\\), then \\(R B=6-x\\) Since \\(\\angle C A B=\\frac{\\pi}{3}\\), then \\(\\angle C B A=\\pi-\\frac{\\pi}{2}-\\frac{\\pi}{3}=\\frac{\\pi}{6}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nConsidering that the area of a sector is given as \\(\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Area of Sector } A P R &amp; =\\frac{1}{2} \\times \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{3} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ \\text { Area of Sector } B R Q &amp; =\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\end{aligned} $$ Since we want the two areas to equal:$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; \\frac{x^2 \\pi}{6}=\\frac{(6-x)^2 \\pi}{6} \\\\ &amp; x^2 \\pi=(6-x)^2 \\pi \\\\ &amp; x^2=(6-x)^2 \\\\ &amp; x^2=36-12 x+x^2 \\\\ &amp; 36-12 x=0 \\\\ &amp; 12(3-x)=0 \\\\ \\end{aligned} $$$$\\therefore x=3$$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>\\(x=\\frac{\\sqrt3}{2}\\)</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:18:23', '2024-03-26 18:18:23'),
(615, NULL, 123, 1, '<p>A necklace is made in the form of a sector of a circle, as shown in the diagram below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/966d9f1c98f50321b2ba26e7112854fb.png\" style=\"height:261px; width:228px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. If the radius is known to be \\(3.5 \\mathrm{~cm}\\), what is the angle \\(\\theta\\), in radians to the nearest 3 decimal places, so that the area is \\(8 \\mathrm{~cm}^2 ?\\)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Another necklace has the same total perimeter, but with radius \\(3 \\mathrm{~cm}\\). What is the required angle \\(\\alpha\\) for this other necklace, in radians?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[3 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 131, '<p>i. The area of the sector is known to be \\(8 \\mathrm{~cm}^2\\).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHence, using the area formula: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 8=\\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\theta \\ [\\theta \\text { is in radians }] \\\\ &amp; 16=r^2 \\theta \\\\ &amp; 16=(3.5)^2 \\theta \\\\ &amp; \\theta=\\frac{16}{3.5^2} \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\theta \\approx 1.306[\\text { nearest } 3 \\text { d.p.] }] \\end{aligned} $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. The perimeter of the necklace is: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Perimeter } &amp; =3.5+3.5+r \\theta \\ [\\text { length of curve is } l \\theta] \\\\ &amp; =7+3.5(1.306) \\ [\\text { From part } i] \\\\ &amp; =11.571 \\mathrm{~cm} \\end{aligned} $$For the second necklace with radius \\(3 \\mathrm{~cm}\\), its perimeter expression may be given as: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Perimeter } &amp; =3+3+r \\alpha \\\\ &amp; =6+3 \\alpha \\end{aligned} $$ Since the perimeter of both necklaces are the same: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 11.571=6+3 \\alpha \\\\ &amp; 3 \\alpha=5.571 \\\\ &amp; \\therefore \\alpha=1.857 \\text { radians } \\end{aligned} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$\\theta=1.306 \\text{ radians}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$\\alpha=5.571 \\text{ radians}$$</p>', '480', 'Medium', '5', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 18:21:44', '2024-03-26 18:21:44'),
