(726, NULL, 144, 1, '<p>Hank leaves island \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) in a canoe and rows \\(136 \\mathrm{~km}\\) on a bearing of \\(75^{\\circ}\\) to island \\(\\mathrm{B} . \\mathrm{He}\\) then rows on a bearing of \\(203^{\\circ}\\) for \\(186 \\mathrm{~km}\\) to island C, as shown in the diagram below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/9c0d79c66b6f4510140fa17f3374db3a.png\" style=\"height:682px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. Show that the size of \\(\\angle A B C=x^{\\circ} \\ \\)<br />\r\n[1 mark]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Find the distance from island \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) to island \\(\\mathrm{A}\\)<br />\r\n[2 marks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. Hanks wants to row from island \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) directly to island \\(\\mathrm{A}\\). On what bearing will he row? Give your answer to the nearest minute<br />\r\n[2 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 134, '<p>i. \\(\\quad\\) Since \\(AN\\) and \\(BN\\) are parallel: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle A B N &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\angle N A B[\\because \\text { Collinear angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-75^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =105^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A B C &amp; =360^{\\circ}-105^{\\circ}-203^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =52^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} \\end{aligned} $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Considering \\(\\triangle A B C\\):</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e1855a84d6c366ea78d0735edfa9ad95.jpeg\" style=\"height:268px; width:236px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} A C^2 &amp; =A B^2+B C^2-2(A B)(B C) \\cos 52^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =136^2+186^2-2 \\times 136 \\times 186 \\cos 52^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 21944.45 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore A C=148 \\mathrm{~km} $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. To find the bearing, we need to first find the value of \\(\\angle A C B, \\angle N C B\\) and \\(\\angle N C A\\)</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/308e45c0b4f56c10de555edcec8c8391.png\" style=\"height:440px; width:300px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finding \\(\\angle A C B\\) using cosine rule:$$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos \\angle A C B &amp; =\\frac{(A C)^2+(B C)^2-(A B)^2}{2(A C)(B C)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{148^2+186^2-136^2}{2 \\times 148 \\times 186} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{3167}{4588} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore \\angle A C B=46^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime} $$Next, we can find the value of \\(\\angle N C B\\) using collinear angles for parallel lines: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N C B &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\angle C B N \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-\\left(360^{\\circ}-203^{\\circ}\\right) \\\\ &amp; =180^{\\circ}-157^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =23^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A C N &amp; =\\angle A C B-\\angle N C B \\\\ &amp; =46^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime}-23^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =23^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime} \\end{aligned} $$Hence, since \\(\\angle A C N=23^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime}\\), the bearing of \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) will be: $$ 360^{\\circ}-23^{\\circ} 21^{\\prime}=336^{\\circ} 39^{\\prime} T $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$\\angle A B C=52^{\\circ}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$AC=122\\text{ km}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part iii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$308^{\\circ} 29^{\\prime} T$$</p>', '540', 'Hard', '5', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 20:58:22', '2024-03-26 20:58:22'),
