(742, NULL, 146, 1, '<p>A hiker walks \\(6 \\mathrm{~km}\\) from camp (point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) ) to point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) in a direction of \\(N 46^{\\circ} E\\). He then walks \\(4 \\mathrm{~km}\\) due east to point \\(\\mathrm{B}\\), as shown in the diagram below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/11b3043a0041521679899c81b3df8023.png\" style=\"height:379px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. Calculate the shortest distance between point B and the camp, giving your answer to the nearest 3 significant figures&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Calculate the bearing of the hiker at point $\\mathrm{B}$ from the camp, giving your answer to the nearest degree&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 134, '<p>i. To calculate the value of \\(\\mathrm{BC}\\) using cosine rule, we must first find the value of \\(\\angle B A C\\)<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo do so, construct interval \\(A N_1\\) such that it points to North:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/e950cbff57958e67df366a453f700e8a.png\" style=\"height:321px; width:400px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle C A N_1 &amp; =180^{\\circ}-46^{\\circ}[\\because \\text { co }- \\text { interior angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =134^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$ Since \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) is due east of \\(\\mathrm{A}, \\angle N_1 A B=90^{\\circ}\\) $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle C A B &amp; =360^{\\circ}-134^{\\circ}-90^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =136^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Hence, now using cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} B C^2 &amp; =A C^2+A B^2-2(A C)(A B) \\cos \\angle C A B \\\\ B C^2 &amp; =6^2+4^2-2(6)(4) \\cos 136^{\\circ} \\\\ B C^2 &amp; \\approx 86.52831 \\\\ \\therefore B C &amp; \\approx 9.30 \\mathrm{~km}[\\text { nearest } 3 \\text { sig fig }] \\end{aligned} $$ii. To find the bearing of \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), we must first find \\(\\angle A C B\\) To do so, we will use cosine rule [sine rule may be used too, but we must check for ambiguous case!]$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\cos \\angle A C B &amp; =\\frac{A C^2+B C^2-A B^2}{2(A C)(B C)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{6^2+9.3^2-4^2}{2(6)(9.3)} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 0.9542 \\\\ \\therefore \\angle A C B &amp; \\approx 17.4055^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Note that it is good habit to avoid rounding too much during our working out to avoid getting an inaccurate answer Hence, the bearing of \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) may be given as: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\text { Bearing } &amp; =46^{\\circ}+17.4055^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 63^{\\circ}[\\text {nearest degree}] \\end{aligned} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$BC=9.30 \\text{ km}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$66^{\\circ}$$</p>', '420', 'Hard', '4', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 21:05:21', '2024-03-26 21:05:21'),
