(748, NULL, 147, 1, '<p>A ship sails \\(120 \\mathrm{~km}\\) from point A to point B on a bearing of \\(145^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T}\\). The ship then sails from point \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) on a bearing of \\(060^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T}\\) to point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\) which is \\(150 \\mathrm{~km}\\) away.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/3a81732e4bc9d227942026cfc58ed49b.jpeg\" style=\"height:283px; width:643px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. Find the distance from point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) to point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), giving your answer correct to two decimal places &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Find the bearing of point \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) from point \\(\\mathrm{C}\\), giving your answer correct to the nearest degree&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 134, '<p>i. First filling in the diagram with the given information:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/468d965b18a625e0d4c795b9c2d84418.jpeg\" style=\"height:211px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since \\(\\angle N A B=145^{\\circ}\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N B A &amp; =180^{\\circ}-145^{\\circ}[\\text { co }- \\text { interior angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =35^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\angle A B C &amp; =60^{\\circ}+35^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =95^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Considering the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} A C^2= &amp; A B^2+B C^2-2(A B)(A C) \\cos \\angle A B C \\\\ = &amp; 120^2+150^2-2(120)(150) \\cos 95^{\\circ} \\\\ = &amp; 40037.6 \\\\ &amp; \\quad \\therefore A C \\approx 200.09 \\mathrm{~km} \\end{aligned} $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. The logic behind this is that if we are able to determine the value of \\(\\angle N C A\\), then the bearing would equal to \\(360^{\\circ}-\\angle N C A\\). To find \\(\\angle N C A\\), we must find \\(\\angle N A C\\) since \\(\\angle N C A=180^{\\circ}-\\angle N A C[\\) co-interior \\(]\\).&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo find \\(\\angle N A C\\), we must find \\(\\angle C A B\\) since \\(\\angle N A C=145^{\\circ}-\\angle C A B\\).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nHence, to find \\(\\angle C A B\\), we consider the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos \\angle C A B &amp; =\\frac{A C^2+A B^2-B C^2}{2(A C)(A B)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{200.09^2+120^2-150^2}{2(200.09)(120)} \\\\ &amp; =0.665 \\end{aligned} $$$$ \\therefore \\angle C A B \\approx 48^{\\circ} \\text { [nearest degree] } $$ Thus, we can find \\(\\angle N A C\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N A C &amp; =145^{\\circ}-48^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =97^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$Thus, we can find \\(\\angle N C A\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} \\angle N C A &amp; =180^{\\circ}-97^{\\circ}[\\text { co }- \\text { interior angles supplementary }] \\\\ &amp; =83^{\\circ} \\end{aligned} $$ Therefore, the bearing will be: $$ 360^{\\circ}-83^{\\circ}=277^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$AC=200.09 \\text{ km}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$291^{\\circ}\\text{T}$$</p>', '480', 'Hard', '4', 1, NULL, '2024-03-26 21:07:52', '2024-03-26 21:07:52');
