(754, NULL, 148, 1, '<p>A boat leaves port \\(\\mathrm{A}\\) on a bearing of \\(300^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T}\\) and sails for four hours at an average speed of \\(12 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}\\) until point \\(X\\).&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSimultaneously, Michael Phelps also leaves from port A and travels due North to island \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) which is \\(25 \\mathrm{~km}\\) from port \\(\\mathrm{A}\\).</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/588de62730755b9a9029df80ab133c0e.jpeg\" style=\"height:245px; width:404px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. Calculate the distance between point \\(X\\) and island B&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Find the bearing of island B from point \\(X\\) to the nearest degree&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[3 marks]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. After spending several hours doing push ups on the island, Michael Phelps swims due South back to point A. How far North of the port will Michael Phelps be when he is directly East of the boat?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 134, '<p>i. 4 hours at an average speed of \\(12 \\mathrm{~km} / \\mathrm{hr}\\) means that the distance \\(\\mathrm{XA}\\) is \\(4 \\times 12=\\) \\(48 \\mathrm{~km}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMoreover, \\(\\angle B A X=360^{\\circ}-300^{\\circ}=60^{\\circ}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHence, to find the value of \\(\\mathrm{BX}\\) we consider the cosine rule: $$ \\begin{gathered} B X^2=A B^2+A X^2-2(A B)(A X) \\cos \\angle B A X \\\\ B X^2=25^2+48^2-2(25)(48) \\cos \\angle 60^{\\circ} \\\\ B X^2=1729 \\\\ \\quad \\therefore B X=\\sqrt{1729} \\mathrm{~km} \\end{gathered} $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Let NX be an interval in the northern direction:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/039d246856cf39f7e1212297ac5ec5d3.jpeg\" style=\"height:223px; width:386px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The bearing of \\(\\mathrm{B}\\) from \\(\\mathrm{X}\\) is given as the angle \\(\\angle N X B\\) To find \\(\\angle N X B\\), we must consider \\(\\angle N X A-\\angle B X A=\\angle N X B\\) $$ \\begin{gathered} \\angle B A X=360^{\\circ}-300^{\\circ}=60^{\\circ} \\\\ \\therefore \\angle N X A=180^{\\circ}-60^{\\circ}=120^{\\circ}[\\text { co - interior angles supplementary }] \\end{gathered} $$ To find \\(\\angle B X A\\), consider the cosine rule:$$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos \\angle B X A &amp; =\\frac{B X^2+X A^2-A B^2}{2(B X)(X A)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1729+48^2-25^2}{2 \\sqrt{1729}(48)} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 0.85375 \\end{aligned} $$\\(\\angle B X A \\approx 31^{\\circ}\\) [nearest degree] Hence, \\(\\angle N X B=120^{\\circ}-31^{\\circ}=89^{\\circ}\\) $$ \\therefore \\text { Bearing }=089^{\\circ} \\mathrm{T} $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. Let the point where Michael Phelps is directly east of point \\(\\mathrm{X}\\) be point \\(\\mathrm{E}\\), with \\(\\angle A E X=90^{\\circ}\\).&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHence, sketching the diagram:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/7c3897bbc2df0e22596446f85fc609c9.jpeg\" style=\"height:198px; width:366px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note that \\(\\angle X A E=\\angle X A B=60^{\\circ}\\)&nbsp;<br />\r\nSince we need to find the value of AE, consider: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\cos 60^{\\circ} &amp; =\\frac{A E}{A X} \\\\ \\therefore A E &amp; =A X \\cos 60^{\\circ} \\\\ &amp; =48 \\times \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ &amp; =24 \\mathrm{~km} \\end{aligned} $$</p>', 'correct', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$BX=\\sqrt{1729} \\text{ km}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$\\text{Bearing}=089^{\\circ}\\text{ T}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part iii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$AE=24\\text{ km}$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '840', 'Hard', '7', 1, NULL, '2024-03-27 13:46:18', '2024-03-27 13:46:18'),
