(775, NULL, 150, 1, '<p>A tourist who is \\(y\\)&nbsp;metres due south of a tower sees the top of it with an angle of elevation \\(10^{\\circ}\\). A second tourist is \\(x\\)&nbsp;metres due east of the tower and sees the top of it with an angle of elevation \\(13^{\\circ}\\). The two tourists are known to be \\(880 \\mathrm{~m}\\)&nbsp;apart</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6b087b186cb07839281cb29e49087c05.png\" style=\"height:376px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. \\(\\quad\\)Show that \\(y=\\frac{h}{\\tan 10^{\\circ}}\\)<br />\r\n[1 mark]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii.\\(\\quad\\)Find the height \\((h)\\)&nbsp;of the tower to the nearest metre<br />\r\n[3 marks]</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 29, 135, '<p>Solution:<br />\r\ni. Considering the triangle below:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/ec7c7a4adab3b32d3e4e2d3ab62f182d.png\" style=\"height:262px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\tan 10^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{y} \\\\ y=\\frac{h}{\\tan 10^{\\circ}} \\end{gathered} $$\\(&nbsp;\\text { ii. Considering the other triangle in our diagram: } \\)</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/02f550d2bbfde90795588daac0c093fa.png\" style=\"height:257px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$ \\begin{gathered} \\therefore \\tan 13^{\\circ}=\\frac{h}{x} \\\\ x=\\frac{h}{\\tan 13^{\\circ}} \\end{gathered} $$ Finally, considering the bottom triangle:\\</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/f552a847406f2d411fa2a67787944727.png\" style=\"height:334px; width:500px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hence, considering the pythagoras theorem: $$ \\begin{gathered} x^2+y^2=880^2 \\\\ \\left(\\frac{h}{\\tan 13}\\right)^2+\\left(\\frac{h}{\\tan 10}\\right)^2=880^2 \\\\ \\frac{h^2}{\\tan ^2 13}+\\fra